The result was the establishment ol a third comitia, the comitia centuriata, which was destined, lor most purposes, to eventually drrow the other two into the shade, and to engross the discussion ol public questions, such as war and peace, legislation- on matters aflecting the con- stitution, the choice of magistrates, and the decision oi all judicial proceedings which involved the ‘caput' ofa Roman citizen. In the comitia centuriata, where each century had a single vote, the in- fluence ol the richer middle class had an irresistible preponderance. In the order which lurnished cavalry, the patrician votes were out- numbered in the proportion ol two to one by those ol the plebeians; while the eighty votes ol the first oi Servius’ infantry classes formed a compact political force which could lose or win the day in a con· tested election, or on a public question upon which opinions differed. The political, however, were not precisely identical with the military centuries; the proportion between the classes was the same, but by the addition ol a proletariate suffrage the number of military com- panies was exceeded by the number ol votes in the comitia by one.

With the expulsion of the sons ol Tarquinius Superbus (circ. 509 n. c.) the kingly govemment ol Rome came to an end. The act had been that ol the patricians; but the plebeians were in lull accord with them, and to the harmony between the leaders ol the two parties was due the introduction ol the Servian constitution by the leges Valeriae, and in particular ol the comitia centuriata, with all the powers aad privileges lately enumerated.
